  "dateModified": "2025-04-15",
  "datePublished": "2025-04-15",
  "description": "The system-level governance condition in which subjects are confused but functional — unable to resolve what is happening, yet still interpreting, engaging, and producing the sensemaking labor that sustains the system. Mere confusion halts participation (people disengage and withdraw); coherent confusion sustains participation by keeping the signal ambiguous enough that interpretation never resolves but never fully fails either. The subject remains in a state of active processing: confused about the situation, but coherent in how they narrate their confusion. The interpretive labor — the takes, threads, analyses, commentary — is not a byproduct of governance; it is the governing mechanism itself, the outermost feedback loop in the cybernetic structure of late-liberal control.",
  "name": "Coherent confusion",
  "publisher": {
